// Phase 5/6 perks catalog (Sims-style aspiration rewards). Players spend
// Ambition Points (AP) earned from any ambition's stage payoffs on perks
// drawn from this universal catalog.
//
// Schema (validated in perks.ts):
//   id          — stable string key
//   nameZh      — zh-CN player-facing name
//   descZh      — zh-CN one-paragraph blurb
//   apCost      — AP price; tier ladder is 1 AP / 2 AP / 4 AP
//   category    — vital | skill | social | economic | combat | faction
//   effect      — discriminated union; system code branches on `kind`.
//                 Phase 5.0 ships effect kinds in this order of risk:
//                   - vitalDecay      : multiplier on the per-tick decay
//                                       of one or all vitals (1.0 = no effect)
//                   - skillXpMul      : multiplier on skill XP gain in a category
//                                       (categories match SkillId)
//                   - wageMul         : multiplier on workSystem wage payout
//                   - shopDiscountMul : multiplier on shop prices (<1 cheaper)
//                   - rentMul         : multiplier on bed nightly rent (<1 cheaper)
//                 Future (combat/faction-tier perks) hook here as they land.
//
// Phase 6.0 ships only the perks above; the combat / faction-leader
// categories are scaffolded but their effects don't yet activate.
//
// Pricing intent: 1 AP = "small permanent quality-of-life nudge", 2 AP =
// "noticeable build choice", 4 AP = "significant lategame reward". Total
// AP across the six starter ambitions is roughly 30-50, so a long career
// can buy a meaningful but not unlimited set.

